.TH "cicdaemon" "8" "July 14 2026" "cicdaemon 1.1" "CIC Commands Manual"
.SH NAME
.PP
cicdaemon \(en CIC host management and compliance daemon
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
cicdaemon < \f[I]COMMAND\f[R] > [ \f[I]OPTION\f[R] ] [ \f[I]HOST\f[R]
\&...
] < \f[I]SUBSYSTEM\f[R] > \&...
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]cicdaemon\f[R] is an orchestrator script for a \f[B]HOST\f[R]\(cqs
given \f[B]SUBSYSTEM\f[R], like its \f[I]identity\f[R],
\f[I]network\f[R], \f[I]dns\f[R], \f[I]time\f[R], \f[I]ssh\f[R], and so
on.
It dispatches a \f[B]COMMAND\f[R] to one or more \f[B]SUBSYSTEMS\f[R],
each of which is resposible for a single concern regarding the host.
\f[B]SUBSYSTEMS\f[R] are NOT specific binaries (but they can be), they
are \f[I]logical parts of a host\f[R] that you want you manage.
.PP
For example, the \f[B]ssh subsystem\f[R] includes not only
\f[B]ssh\f[R](1), but \f[B]sshd\f[R](8), as well as their respective
configuration files, like \f[I]/etc/ssh/sshd_config\f[R], or even
ensuring \f[I]\(ti/.ssh\f[R] has the proper \f[B]700\f[R] permissions
through \f[B]chmod\f[R](1).
See \f[B]SUBSYSTEMS\f[R] for more info.
.PP
If no \f[B]COMMAND\f[R] is specified, \f[B]COMMAND\f[R] defaults to
\f[B]show\f[R] or \f[B]ls\f[R], depending on whether a \f[B]HOST\f[R] is
provided, and the \f[B]SUBSYSTEM\f[R].
.PP
If no \f[B]HOST\f[R] is specified, \f[B]HOST\f[R] defaults to the local
machine.
.PP
\f[B]cicdaemon\f[R] itself has two purposes:
.IP \(bu 2
Bring newly\-provisioned virtual machines to a known baseline
.IP \(bu 2
Verify they stay there
.PP
The desired state is read from the inventory file at
\f[B]/etc/cicdaemon/inventory.yaml\f[R], and parsed with
\f[B]yq\f[R](1).
Host details should never be hard\-coded in the handlers or the
dispatcher itself.
.SH COMMANDS
\f[B]init\f[R] [\f[I]SUBSYSTEM\f[R] \&...]
.PP
Run a \f[I]SUBSYSTEM\f[R]\(cqs init phase (if applicable).
If no \f[I]SUBSYSTEM\f[R], initialize all \f[B]SUBSYSTEMS\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]ls\f[R]
.PP
List active subsystems
.PP
\f[B]audit\f[R]
.PP
Run all \f[B]SUBSYSTEMS\f[R] in \f[B]audit\f[R] mode.
.SH SUBSYSTEMS
A \f[B]SUBSYSTEM\f[R] is a specific area of concern on a host, not the
\f[I]binary\f[R] or \f[I]script\f[R] that implements it.
\f[I]That does not necessarily mean a subsystem can\(cqt be a specific
binary\f[R], just that subsystems should never be thought of as a binary
themselves.
Documentation, and even in\-line comments are key here, since I want to
keep this modular.
.PP
Each subsystem will be marked with one of (\f[B]audit\f[R],
\f[B]enforce\f[R]), (\f[B]audit\f[R]), or (\f[B]enforce\f[R]), which
represents what the subsystem is capable of.
.PP
\f[B]audit mode\f[R] means a subsystem will report issues, but will not
attempt or prompt you to reconcile those issues.
.PP
\f[B]enforce mode\f[R] means a subsystem will attempt to reconcile an
issue, if it is capable of doing so.
.PP
\f[B]ssh\f[R] (\f[B]audit\f[R], \f[B]enforce\f[R])
